The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                        
	London: Three-time Tour de France winner Alberto Contador of Spain was suspended Thursday after failing a dope test, in the latest drug scandal to hit cyclings most prestigious event. Contador announced that he had tested positive for Clenbuterol, a banned substance, but blamed it on food contamination.        
	New Delhi: With the Indian Hockey Federation failing to clarify its stand on its merger with IWHF, the sports ministry Thursday advised the sport body to postpone its polls, scheduled for October 3.        
	Belgrade: Serbia have chosen their favourite hardcourt surface for the Dec. 3 to 5 Davis Cup final against France in the Belgrade Arena, the Serbian Tennis Association said.        
	Khanty Mansiysk: On a day of mixed fortunes, Indian men thrashed Turkmenistan 3-1, but the womens team suffered a 0.5-0.5 defeat to Russia One, in the 8th round of the 39th Chess Olympiad here Thursday.        
	Taipei: None of the Indian golfers in fray managed to break par with Rahil Gangjee, being the best-placed among his compatriots at tied 18th with a two-over 74 in the opening round of the $500,000 Mercuries Taiwan Masters here Thursday.        
	Dubai: Virender Sehwag is one of the four current leading cricketers, who have been chosen by the ICC as its ambassadors for year 2010-2011. Sri Lanka captain Kumar Sangakkara, Englands World Twenty20 winning captain Paul Collingwood, Australia vice-captain Michael Clarke are the other ambassadors.        
	Harare: Grant Flower will revive his international career at the age of 39 for Zimbabwes tour of South Africa next month. Flower, the younger brother of England team director Andy, said on Thursday that he will play for his country for the first time since his international career was cut short in 2004 by a dispute between Zimbabwes players and its cricket board.        
	London: Batsmen will no longer be able to ask for play to be called off because of bad light, according to one of the eight minor changes to the laws of cricket set to take effect Friday. The MCC  the custodian of the laws of the game  will allow only umpires the right to decide whether play can be halted because of darkness.        
	Lahore: The PCB is not providing any financial assistance to the three suspended players in their legal battle against the ICC.    
	The three have hired lawyers who are representing the players in their effort to get the suspensions removed and their names cleared in the spot-fixing allegations, a PCB source said.                                                                                                                                                       
